segments.text: He said, did you know that the public health grades have been posted?
And I said, no, I didn't know that.
He said, as usual, you made an A.
That was his first words to me in four years.
That man and I finished at the same time, and then later I found out that his license had been suspended.
You know, that's another irony.
His license was suspended for unethical practice.
But there are many subtle ways in which discrimination is practiced.
How about as a student here, you were probably in your class, you were probably, what, there were 30, about 20 or 30, 25 or about that graduated in your class, I would say?
No, no, we were 64.
Oh, yeah, I see.
The list was that long?
I read it down and I didn't realize it was that long.
No, see, in my class, at that time there were
accepting 64 a year, and I told you that three had joined us, you see, from a previous class, so it made 67, but some of them didn't make it, see.
So, we only finished, I don't remember exactly, but it seemed to me that we finished with about 64 people.
Okay, and you were, were you the only, you were the only Mexican?
Oh, absolutely.
I was the only one for years.
Did you feel that you were treated differently by your instructors?
No, sir.
Not by my teachers.
I never experienced any discrimination from my teachers here.
No.
Why do you think that?
Why do you think that was?
Well, I think that my teachers, and when I say my teachers, I'm talking about Dr. Jaggi, Dr. Turk, Dr.
I think that those people represented a special breed who had a lot of vision and who could look into the future and see that there was no place for discrimination on a campus such as ours.
I never, from my teacher, I never received any indication of discrimination.
It was rather
Well, from other departments.
I remember- What do you mean from other departments?
I remember an English course that I took.
I took an English course under a guy by the name of Greer.
I'll never forget him as long as I live.
Because- And this was back in 43 or 44?
It was 1943, in January 1943.
I had a course- wait a minute.
No, it was in the summer of 1943.
Okay.
You see in in high school I graduated third out of a class of 207.
My grades are extremely high and I was co-editor of my high school paper so I have always scored very high grades in English in composition.
I have written professionally and so forth and all of my teachers have praised
my English.
But when I got to this guy, Greer, I took sophomore English under him.
It was English 203, if I remember correctly.
He used to return my papers unmarked with a D or an F, every paper that I turned into.
So when I went to him and I said, look, I'm not going to learn anything in this course if you don't tell me what mistakes I'm making or how I can improve my grade in your course.
Because you return my papers unmarked.
That doesn't teach me anything.
He said, I don't like your style.
And that's what he gave me.
I got a D in English after I had been a straight-A student in English up to that time.
As a matter of fact, I saved those papers.
And one time when I was walking down the hall of the academic building, I met a former English teacher of mine.
And he said, how are you getting along in sophomore English?
And I told him I'm failing that course.
He said, my God, how can that be?
I said, I'll tell you what, I have here in my notebook a bunch of papers that have been returned to me unmarked except for the grade.
He said, let me have him.
And he took him with him.
And then the next time he saw me, he said, if I were you, I'd take these papers to the head of the English department and tell him what this guy's doing to you.
Well, I think of an overt sign of discrimination.
Did you take those papers?
No.
No, I didn't take those papers anywhere because, you know, A&M has a system here.
You can't beat the system.
A lot of other people have tried, and I'm not going to be the first one to stand up against the Board of Regents or anybody else, because you can't win.
I'm nearing now the end of my professional career.
I'm eligible for retirement.
I feel that my speaking out on this issue
would just create a hell of a lot of enemies and uh and and not get anything done.
I wrote a letter to President Miller warning him that unless this this university reversed its trends to discriminate against Hispanics that we may be in for some
chastisement from the Department of Health, Education, and Welfare.
And two weeks after I wrote that letter, they sent a team from Washington out here to- I never told Washington anything.
As a matter of fact, the letter I wrote to President Miller was not sent through channels.
It was sent directly to his home.
And I called attention to a disproportion of
disproportionate low number of Hispanics attending the university.
There's 31,000 people here.
Less than 1% are Mexicans in a state that has 30%.
It doesn't make sense.
I want to ask you a question.
I had a senior administrator at this university tell me last year that
Mexican-Americans have all seen A&M as an opportunity to advance and have always realized that there's no discrimination against them and that's why we always have Mexican-Americans.
Like you say, we have a lot of Mexican-American Aggie former students who are quite proud of being former students here and obviously you disagree with that.
Of course I disagree with it because

uh like I say less than one percent of the students are Mexican-American now those are not my figures they were published in the battalion they're items of common knowledge I saved that article it's I don't know I can't find it right now I'm just moving into this office but uh there were those statistics reveal that uh very very few
Mexican-Americans in this institution.
I don't know why.
I have talked to several people in this department about it, and they said, well, you're distorting, you know, the facts.
And I asked them, how am I distorting the facts?
I said, because in the first place, if you take all the Mexican-Americans in the state of Texas, how many of them would have the money to send their children to college?
See, that knocks out a lot of that 30% figure that you're citing.
In other words, very few people from minority groups would have the money to go to college.
And out of those that do have the money to go to college, well, a lot of them pick careers that are not offered at A&M.
For example, law, and they go to the University of Texas.

or where they go to to some university like Kingsville A&I or to some other one but that I don't think that I don't think that that is factual I don't think that the number of people of Mexican-American descent are so
destitute that they can't send their children to college.
I don't believe that.
And then, of course, a logical question is why isn't there some sort of a scholarship program?
No, you know, let me give you a couple of examples that I think are significant.
People here that reject the idea that there's
discrimination against Hispanics.
Or very quick to point out that several years ago we had a commander of the Corps of Cadets here from Laredo who was Hispanic.
If what you say is true, that example there will negate anything else you say.
The guy was so outstanding that it would have been difficult to keep him out of the slot of commander of the Corps.
Did you know him?
No, I didn't.
The name is Gutierrez.
I knew him and I knew, of course, his father I went to school with.
They came from a very wealthy family, Laredo, who experienced some very, very hard times following the death of their father.
But the example that I wanted to give you was the example of McClure, the black student, who came to this campus and was president of the student body.
What year was that?
Do you remember?
A couple of years ago.
I mean, when that guy, he was recruited, I think,
I don't have any direct evidence of this, but I feel that he was recruited because they saw in him a tremendous potential.
And he was a gifted speaker.
As a matter of fact, to quote Wayne Stark of the Memorial Student Center, he said, when they made McClure, they threw the mold away.
He was not exceptional.
And as a senior at A&M, he delivered three commencement exercises in this area.
Where'd he go?
I heard that he had gone to Washington to work for Senator Tower.
And I think that you can expect to hear more about this fellow on the floor.
He's a black.

But you see, my response to some of these allegations that blacks and Mexicans or Hispanics don't have the intellectual capacity to make it through here, and I've heard that from people that should never have told me that.
People are in very highly placed positions here.
Really?
That's right.
In the vet school?
No.
But in the administration?
Well one of them is a veterinarian, but he's not in vet school.
You heard that from the administrators?
He told me that in his opinion blacks didn't have the intellectual capacity to be veterinarians.
That the only way that we could have
an increased number of blacks as veterinarians would be to reduce the admission requirements so that they would qualify.
Of course, I don't condone that.
I don't advocate that at all.
I think that you could find that the A&M could find a respectable number of minority students if they sought them, if they made some legitimate
efforts to seek outstanding students in the public schools of Texas and interest them in the veterinary profession.
I believe that we could get a much higher number than we have had in the past.
But you see, now you have to recognize one outstanding fact in all of this, in all of these discussions, that
since my resignation as director of the Institute of Tropical Veterinary Medicine, I don't have any any reason anymore for mingling with other department members on this campus.
And so my communication now with the rest of the campus has been very seriously curtailed as a result of the fact that I'm not an administrator anymore.
I was an administrator for
for two years.
No, wait a minute, three years.
Were you the first Mexican-American to be appointed to the faculty?
Of the College of Indian Medicine?
Yes.
Well, yeah, I can't answer that question.
I think that they had one or two others, but they didn't stick around.
I know that I'm the only full professor who's been appointed to the College of Animal Medicine as a Mexican American.
There was another guy who had a Spanish surname, but he couldn't speak one word of Spanish.
And so he, you know, he was used as a body to indicate that this man was a minority, but he wasn't.
He had a Spanish surname, but
That's all.
He knew no Spanish and he had never been raised in a Spanish environment.
He came from another state and so forth.
But I know that if you visit other agencies on this campus, you will find reams and stacks
of reference material to contradict everything that I had told you, because it's very easy to do that.
But on the other hand, I think it would be quite difficult for anybody to say, yes, we do have a very active recruitment program, and here is the evidence right here.
We have sent people to Laredo.
We have sent people to Eagle Pass.
We sent people to Brownsville or McAllen or Kingsville to find interest in the A&M.
I don't have access to any such information.
I've never sought it.
Why don't we try it?
Why don't we have that type of program, do you think?
I don't know.
I don't know.
I know that the people will say,
The head of the Former Students Association, he's a Mexican.
There's a guy by the name of Fernandez, Raul Fernandez.
Did you know that?
He's head of the alumni.
This year, as a matter of fact, he's president, isn't he?
Yeah.
It's a one-year, it's elected one-year term, right?
Yeah.
It's a one-year position.
What I'd like to see here is, I would like to see

a sincere effort you see of recruitment I don't like for people to try and snow me with figures and papers because anybody can do that but what I'm talking about is I would like to personally see the names of people who are on a committee that
has designed a program for recruitment of minority groups to the College of Internal Medicine as well as to other departments within this campus.
Have you ever become involved in any of it?
No.
Why not?
Well, I have for the first time in my life since I, you know,
The answer to your question is very complex.
I have married a wonderful girl from Michigan.
She's not Mexican-American.
She's Dutch.
My kids are mongrels.
I tell them they're mongrels.
They've got Spanish blood and Indian blood
and I myself am part Irish and my wife's Dutch and so I have been in the Army for so long there was no opportunity for me to participate viably in any Chicano movement of any kind.
I never joined the LULACs and I never been a part of the

or the Raza Unida or anything like this, and being in the Army, you know, those political affiliations are not encouraged more around quite a bit, and really don't sink your roots very deep into any community.
But here, I've spent now about 16 years of my life here in this area, and I designed, built my own home here.
I have felt many times that to join one of these politically active groups would be, I think, polarizing people of my ancestry too much.
Yet, there's several groups that have been very effective in the
in the effort to enhance the social aspects of the lives of Hispanics.
And I think the technical and also the job opportunities have been increased by a lot of these groups.
Primarily, some of them are quite militant.
Primarily the American GI Forum.
Yes?
Is this what you wanted?
You said you called down.
This is a heavier suspension.
No, I didn't call down.
It must have been Dr. Hellman.
I have not called you about that, but he's injected those mice.
Well, he did, and nothing happened.
No, I didn't call.
I told him I'd give him a heavier suspension.
Would you give that to him, please, sir?
His office is dark.
I'd be glad to take that.
Should that be refrigerated until the injection is made?
Yes, sir.
We're doing a count on it now.
Okay.
But it's a much heavier suspension than the previous one.
Okay, thank you.
No, that's a good question, you know.
Why haven't I joined any of these groups?
As a matter of fact, I was just looking before you came over here.
One of these people or one of these groups wrote me an invitation here to attend a convention that's going to be held in Austin.
It's called, let me see,
Something about the Chicanos in Higher Education.
The Association of Chicanos in Higher Education, they call themselves TACHE, T-A-C-H-E. And they're gonna have a convention in Austin next month.
Like I said, I've never joined any of these groups.
It's not because I'm opposed to their objectives.
But I'm not at all known in the LULAC.
I'm not at all known in the American GI Forum.
So I felt that it was too late in my professional career to really make any significant contribution to any of these groups since I had never participated before.
So you decided not to go over to Austin?
Well, I have not decided.
but I have never attended any of their conferences.
I don't even know whether there's any active chapter of Thatcher here on this campus.
There must be, but I don't know about it.
In short, I have not gone out of my way to join any of these groups
who espoused the cause of the Chicano or the Latin American or the Hispanic.
Now here in this community, I was the director of the Black and White Ball Association in 1978.
And what exactly is that?
Okay, the Black and White is called the Bryan College Station Black and White Ball Association.
This is an organization

of both Anglos and Hispanics, which was formed in the early 30s in an effort to bring together people of both backgrounds to see if they could dispel some of the instances of discrimination and really try to understand each other's culture.
And every
significant city in Texas that is south of here, particularly, has a local organization.
And the objectives of this organization, which is a loosely organized association, we don't have any ties to any other one.
It's just organized locally.
Ours, for example, is organized not only to promote better relations between the two cultures, but also to give scholarships to children whose parents are in need of some financial assistance.
That is the only reason for the existence of the Bryan College Station Black and White Ball Association.
I would like to tell you why the name Black and White Ball is introduced.
It is not because of the melanization of a person's skin, but rather because of the attire that is customary or traditional to wear at these functions.
They hold a dance once a year, and to this dance is a very formal occasion.
and you're only permitted to wear either black or white.
Either a black tuxedo or a white tuxedo or a combination of black and white.
And the objectives, as I said, our particular association exists only to help needy students go to college.
during my tour as president in 1978, we gave 12 scholarships that ranged between four and $500.
And this year, this last year, 1979, they gave an equal number of scholarships.
So that's about $5,000.
It's a non-profit organization.
Where do you get the funds?
We get the funds from several sources.
I think probably the greatest, the most productive source of funds has been the printing of a brochure that is handed out
to the people who have bought a ticket to the dance.

And in that brochure, it's full of advertisements, and the local merchants have paid to advertise in these brochures, and we have had several hundred printed up, and that has provided us with the greatest source of our income.
Also, of course, the dance itself.
We charge $10 per person, but with this goes a breakfast and contributions from people.
We have managed to...
When I took this organization over in 1978, they had no constitution.
They had never even applied for an IRS tax-exempt status.
So they were paying taxes?
They never paid any taxes because they had made very little money.
Oh, I see.
You see, the IRS never questioned their receipts because they were, you know, very nominal, very modest, but now
when we formed a constitution and elected officers and spelled out who the officers would be and how they would be elected and when the meeting would be held.
You know, a constitution, no organization should exist without a constitution.
And then on the heels of that, I wrote to the IRS and after filling out a tremendous number of forms, they granted us tax exempt status.

And so now, why they recognize the Black and White Ball Association as being a charitable organization that had no desire to make any profits, is all the money is turned over in the spring to those students who have applied for the scholarships and have been selected by their committee.
and have manifested some, have substantiated in some way the fact that they have been accepted by an institution of higher learning, and it's been a very successful program.
And are these just basically poor students?
Yes, but you see, here's something that the Anglo residents of this community
have never taken time out to learn.
These scholarships are not given only to Hispanics.
As a matter of fact, out of the 12 that were the recipients in 1978, I think only one was Hispanic.
The rest of them were Anglos.
And this year, maybe one or two were Hispanics.
So the recipients of these is not based on
on color, or creed, or nationality, or you see, it's for both cultures.
I remember calling the mayor of College Station one time and asking him for a country.
